### Step 1: MCS Lock Implementation

The MCS lock is a scalable spin-lock where threads form a queue when they cannot acquire the lock, so they do not continuously spin on the same variable. This is a simplified version tailored for understanding:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicReference;

class MCSLock {
    static class MCSNode {
        volatile boolean locked = false;
        volatile MCSNode next = null;
    }

    private final AtomicReference<MCSNode> queue = new AtomicReference<>(null);

    public void lock(MCSNode node) {
        MCSNode predecessor = queue.getAndSet(node);
        if (predecessor != null) {
            node.locked = true;
            predecessor.next = node;
            while (node.locked) {} // Spin
        }
    }

    public void unlock(MCSNode node) {
        if (node.next == null) {
            if (queue.compareAndSet(node, null)) {
                return; // No one is waiting
            }
            while (node.next == null) {} // Wait for successor
        }
        node.next.locked = false;
        node.next = null;
    }
}
```

